<HTML>
<HEAD>
<TITLE>The Management of Radioactive Waste - Radioactive waste management as practised and planned within the fuel cycle</TITLE>
</HEAD>
<BODY BGCOLOR="#ffffcc">
<FONT SIZE=6><B>Decommissioning of nuclear facilities</B></FONT>
<IMG SRC="http://www.uilondon.org/bluline.gif" WIDTH=100%>
<P>
Most of the waste arising when decommissioning and dismantling old reactors is low level short-lived waste.  Large volumes can be decontaminated and declassified, and so be handled as normal industrial wastes.  Of the remaining waste, most is low level short-lived waste similar to operational waste, and so will have the same treatment and be disposed of in the same repositories. 
<P>
Only a small part of the waste in some internal parts of the reactor has relatively high activity.  Final disposal of these wastes can be in the same repositories as intermediate level operational wastes, with appropriate technical barriers, or as high level wastes.  Some will be encapsulated and disposed of in the same manner as directly disposed of used fuel. 
<P>
On to <A HREF="http://www.uilondon.org/waste66.html">Waste from medicine, industry and research</A>
<BR>Back to <A HREF="http://www.uilondon.org/waste.html">The Management of Radioactive Waste</A>

